    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-03-17T05:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-03-17T05:10:00-05:00" n="880"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d880">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/3–1054: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief, Far East (<persName corresp="#p_HGJE1"
                            type="from">Hull</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Joint Chiefs of
                            Staff</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>operational immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-03-17T19:10:00+09:00"
                            >March 17, 1954—7:10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>C 67435. Exclusive for <persName corresp="#p_RAAW1">Radford</persName>. Ref:
                        [<gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>] 958438.<note n="1" xml:id="d880fn1"
                        >See <ref target="#d879fn1">footnote 1</ref>, <hi rend="italic">
                            <ref target="#d880">supra</ref>
                        </hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>I have obtained from <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> copy of
                        ltr from Pres <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> to Pres <persName
                            corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> dated 11 March.<note n="1"
                            target="d880fn2">See <ref target="#d879fn1">footnote 1</ref>, <hi
                                rend="italic">
                                <ref target="#d880">supra</ref>
                            </hi>.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>I am convinced Pres <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> and his mil
                        leaders are well aware of the inevitable defeat of any unilateral effort on
                        his part to atk Communists in order to unify Korea. <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> has been informed that unilateral
                        action would not be supported by the US with either troops or supplies. The
                        ltr is therefore, in my opinion, strictly political in nature and designed
                        for the purpose of obtaining additional commitments from the US.</item>
                    <pb facs="0648" n="1766" xml:id="pg_1766"/>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The first course of action desired by Pres <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                            >Rhee</persName> is contrary to our policies. The alternative course
                        would be beyond the capabilities of Korean manpower and economy and if ever
                        achieved would encourage <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> to
                        believe he had the means successfully to undertake offensive action against
                        North Korea.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Both courses I consider completely unacceptable.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>I consider it equally unacceptable to permit Pres <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> to think that we cannot enter the
                        Geneva conf without <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                        participation.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Recommend that any reply contain the fol: <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Rejection of both his proposed alternatives and refusal to support
                                either one.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>In the interests of a real effort to achieve agreements leading
                                toward peaceful relations among nations, the Geneva conf must be
                                held and should be attended by representatives of all govts
                                concerned. In view of <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> deep
                                concern in the matter, it is hoped that it will send its
                                representatives. For it not to do so would not prevent the
                                functioning of the conf, but would be an indication to Communist
                                govts of a lack of solidarity among the free peoples and possible
                                agreement on Korean affairs without participation of <gloss
                                    target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> representatives.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                            <item>The position of the US govt, should Pres <persName
                                    corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> decide to take unilateral
                                action, must be once more clearly stated.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</label>
                            <item>In view of the mil implications of this problem, consideration
                                might be given as to whether I should accompany Amb <persName
                                    corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> when he delivers ans to Pres
                                Rhees ltr.<note n="2" xml:id="d880fn3">According to telegram 926
                                    from Seoul, Mar. 22, 1954, <persName corresp="#p_HGJE1"
                                        >Hull</persName> was not present when <persName
                                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>’s reply was
                                    delivered to <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>; for
                                    text of telegram 926, see <ref target="frus1952-54v16#pg_48"
                                        >vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">xvi</hi>, p. 48</ref>. President
                                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>’s reply to
                                        <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s letter was
                                    transmitted in telegram 748, Mar. 20, and is printed <ref
                                        target="frus1952-54v16#pg_44">
                                        <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 44</ref>.</note>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
